<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1871-07-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1871-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="139" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 2.</note>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Bancroft</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Fish</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 249.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1871-07-29"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 29, 1871</date>. (Received August 18.)</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: This day, at a quarter before 1, I took
                            the British chargé in my carriage to the Foreign Office, where we
                            delivered simultaneously formal notes, identical in terms, addressed to
                            Prince Bismarck, chancellor of the empire, requesting the German Emperor
                            to accept the office of Arbiter on the northwestern boundary question,
                            under the treaty of Washington. I annex a copy of the note.<seg type="margin">Joint notes presented to the German
                            Government.</seg></p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>I remain, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>GEO. BANCROFT.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>